Locked and loaded. Here is Course 2 in the exact “Learn Your Way” pattern: personalize first, then generate synchronized views with embedded checks. I align naming and scope with Google’s certificate track, and I keep the modalities, quizzes, and “Glows and Grows” feedback that Learn Your Way highlights as key to the retention gain. ([Google Research][1])

# Course 2: Ask Questions to Make Data-Driven Decisions (18 hours)

**Course overview:** This course upgrades learners from vague goals to testable, decision-ready questions and clear stakeholder communication. Each module follows Learn Your Way’s two-stage pipeline: we first adapt the text to the learner’s level and interests, then we emit synchronized representations, including immersive text with embedded questions, narrated slide outlines, audio teacher-student scripts, and mind maps, plus short adaptive quizzes. This aligns with Learn Your Way’s multimodal, personalized experience that showed higher immediate and 3 to 5 day retention. ([Google Research][1])
**Google parity:** Course title and emphasis match the Google Data Analytics Certificate sequence and descriptions that stress stakeholder communication and structured thinking. ([Grow with Google][2])

**Hours and sequencing:**

* Module 1: 8 hours
* Module 2: 8 hours
* Capstone: 2 hours integrated at the end of Module 2 to reach 18 total

**Tools used lightly:** Sheets or Slides for storyboards, SQL sandbox for simple cohort pulls to support a narrative, Tableau screenshots for before or after visuals. This mirrors the toolchain highlighted across the Google certificate. ([Grow with Google][2])

---

## Module table: titles, hours, objectives, prerequisites, success criteria

| Module | Title                                     | Hours | Objectives                                                                                                          | Prereqs    | Success criteria                                                                                |
| ------ | ----------------------------------------- | ----: | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| C2-M1  | Asking Better Questions with Stakeholders |     8 | Convert goals into SMART questions, map decisions to metrics, run stakeholder interviews and clarify constraints    | C1 modules | Produces a ranked question backlog with metrics, cohorts, time windows, risks, and data sources |
| C2-M2  | Data Storytelling and Narrative Structure |     8 | Build story arcs, design slide-narrative pairs, create before or after comparisons, tailor messages to stakeholders | C2-M1      | Delivers a 6 to 8 slide narrative with clear takeaway, supported by a simple analysis artifact  |

---

# Module packages

Below each JSON object is a concise human-readable rendering. All representations are generated from the personalized source to keep them synchronized, which is a core Learn Your Way design choice. ([Google Research][1])

### C2-M1 JSON

```json
{
  "module_id": "C2-M1",
  "title": "Asking Better Questions with Stakeholders",
  "hours": 8,
  "objectives": [
    "Transform business goals into SMART, decision-ready questions",
    "Map decisions to metrics, cohorts, and time windows",
    "Run concise stakeholder interviews and clarify constraints and risks"
  ],
  "prerequisites": ["C1-M1", "C1-M2"],
  "success_criteria": [
    "Produces a prioritized backlog of 6-10 SMART questions linked to decisions and metrics",
    "Documents assumptions, data provenance, and risks",
    "Chooses a minimal analysis path that can falsify or confirm hypotheses"
  ],
  "personalization": {
    "grade_level_adaptation": "Undergraduate entry level",
    "interest_hook": "business",
    "learning_style_plan": ["visual", "auditory", "kinesthetic"]
  },
  "representations": {
    "immersive_text": {
      "sections": [
        {
          "heading": "From goals to decisions to questions",
          "content": "Start with the decision deadline and the person who decides. Translate a goal like 'grow weekly active users' into a SMART question with a target, cohort, and timeframe. Every question must imply a metric and an available dataset."
        },
        {
          "heading": "Stakeholder interviews in 5 moves",
          "content": "Define outcome, constraints, success signals, deadlines, and acceptable tradeoffs. Capture unknowns as risks. Confirm the metric dictionary to prevent ambiguity."
        }
      ],
      "embedded_questions": [
        {
          "anchor_section": "From goals to decisions to questions",
          "mcq": {
            "stem": "Which is the best metric for a question about new user activation quality?",
            "choices": ["Total sessions", "7-day retention for new users", "Total installs", "All-time revenue"],
            "answer": "7-day retention for new users",
            "why": "Activation quality should be measured on a defined new-user cohort over a short window."
          }
        }
      ],
      "timeline": ["Identify decision", "Define metric and cohort", "List constraints", "Draft questions", "Plan analysis"],
      "mnemonic": {"topic": "Interview flow", "sentence": "Decide, Define, Limit, Draft, Do"}
    },
    "narrated_slides": {
      "slides": [
        {
          "title": "Decision first",
          "bullets": ["Who decides", "By when", "What will change"],
          "speaker_notes": "Decisions anchor the analysis. Without a decision owner and deadline, questions drift and metrics sprawl."
        },
        {
          "title": "SMART plus risks",
          "bullets": ["Specific metric and cohort", "Timebox", "Assumptions and risks"],
          "speaker_notes": "Make risks explicit, then design a minimal analysis to test the riskiest assumption first."
        }
      ]
    },
    "audio_lesson_script": {
      "dialogue": [
        {"role": "Teacher", "text": "Marketing asks for 'more engaged users.' What do you ask first?"},
        {"role": "Student", "text": "Who is deciding, by when, and which engagement metric matters for that decision."}
      ],
      "misconception_checks": ["Picking metrics before clarifying the decision", "Hiding risks and assumptions"]
    },
    "mind_map": {
      "root": "Decision-aligned questioning",
      "nodes": [
        {"parent": "root", "label": "Decision owner"},
        {"parent": "root", "label": "Deadline"},
        {"parent": "root", "label": "Metric and cohort"},
        {"parent": "root", "label": "Assumptions and risks"}
      ]
    }
  },
  "hands_on": {
    "labs": [
      {"tool": "Sheets", "task": "Write and score 8 SMART questions for a funnel scenario", "dataset": "Toy app events CSV", "check": "Each question has metric, cohort, time window, and decision tag"},
      {"tool": "SQL", "task": "Compute 7-day retention for a 'new users' cohort to support one question", "dataset": "Sample events DB", "check": "Two tables joined, cohort window respected, retention rate computed with clear denominator"}
    ],
    "datasets": [
      {"name": "Mobile App Events Sample", "source": "Kaggle", "license": "CC BY or CC BY-NC", "link": "https://www.kaggle.com/"}
    ]
  },
  "adaptive_quiz": {
    "items": [
      {"id": "c2m1-q1", "difficulty": "easy", "type": "mcq", "stem": "Which element is missing in 'Increase weekly revenue 10 percent'?", "answer": "Cohort or segment", "rationale": "SMART requires a clearly defined audience or segment."},
      {"id": "c2m1-q2", "difficulty": "medium", "type": "short", "stem": "Name one risky assumption in a sign-up conversion analysis and how you would test it.", "answer": "Attribution of campaigns to sessions is accurate, test via controlled cohort or stricter matching.", "rationale": "Surface a key risk and a falsification path."}
    ],
    "summary_feedback": {
      "glows": ["Good linkage of metrics to decisions"],
      "grows": ["Cohort definitions need precise entry rules"],
      "next_steps": ["Rewrite two questions with explicit cohort and time window, then retake c2m1-q1 at hard difficulty"]
    }
  },
  "portfolio_artifact": {
    "deliverable": "Decision brief and question backlog for a chosen product area",
    "rubric": ["Decision clarity", "Metric validity", "Risk articulation", "Communication quality"],
    "github_requirements": ["repo with /brief and /backlog", "README containing glossary and metric dictionary"]
  },
  "accessibility": ["Alt text for diagrams", "Captioned narration", "Keyboard accessible quiz elements"],
  "ethics_and_bias": ["Avoid metric gaming, document data provenance and consent for user data"],
  "time_on_task": {"reading": 1.5, "videos": 1, "labs": 4, "assessments": 1.5}
}
```

**Readable rendering:** You will practice turning stakeholder goals into SMART questions, selecting decision-aligned metrics, and running minimal analysis to test risks. This matches Course 2’s Google focus on stakeholder communication and structured thinking. ([GoogleCerts][3])

